BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:75dcbaf0b356805e@swarthmore-dash-calendar
DTSTAMP:20260308T112827Z
DTSTART:20260316T201500Z
DTEND:20260316T211500Z
SUMMARY:Marriage Refuge: Shared Temporalities of Girlhood in Imperial Japan
 ese Literature
DESCRIPTION:Organized by: ['Japanese'\, 'Modern Languages and Literatures']
 \\nCategory: Lecture/Panel Discussion\\nMarina NascimentoPh.D. Candidate\
 , University of Pennsylvania This talk will explore how Japanese-language 
 literature across the Japanese Empire fostered a shared temporal imaginary
  for schoolgirls confronting the uncertain threshold between graduation an
 d marriage. Focusing on Yoshiya Nobuko’s Yellow Rose (1923) and Yang C
 h’ien-ho’s The Season When the Flowers Bloom (1942)\, I argue that g
 irls’ fiction offered emotional vocabularies and narrative structures th
 rough which young women across the empire\, whether in Tokyo or colonial T
 aiwan\, grappled with similar anxieties around autonomy\, desire\, and (co
 lonial) modernity.\\nDetails: https://swatcentral.swarthmore.edu/?trumbaEm
 bed=view%3Devent%26eventid%3D1358634041
LOCATION:Kohlberg Room 115-Classroom
URL:https://swatcentral.swarthmore.edu/?trumbaEmbed=view%3Devent%26eventid%
 3D1358634041
CATEGORIES:Lecture/Panel Discussion
END:VEVENT
