SUMMARY:G&A: Budgeting Workshop
DESCRIPTION:Organized by: ['Institutional Relations']\\nCategory: Training/
 Workshop\\nPlease join Christy Brydges\, the College’s Grant Account
 ant\, for an exciting mini-training session on budget development f
 or external grants. The budget is a crucial part of the proposal 
 detailing the anticipated project costs. The budget showcases to th
 e funding agency that we are equipped with the necessary resource
 s to achieve the sponsored project’s goals and objectives. Covered 
 topics will include an overview of allowable costs\, the basis of creatin
 g an effective budget for a variety of sponsors\, and the power of a bu
 dget justification.   Who Should Attend? Are you new to budget develop
 ment or are you an experienced principal investigator (PI)\, perhaps look
 ing to expand your budgeting knowledge and enhance your research portfolio
 ? There is something for all!\\nDetails: https://swatcentral.swarthmore.ed
 u/?trumbaEmbed=view%3Devent%26eventid%3D1362653703
LOCATION:Old Science Hall Room 215-Classroom
URL:https://swatcentral.swarthmore.edu/?trumbaEmbed=view%3Devent%26eventid%
 3D1362653703
CATEGORIES:Training/Workshop
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:1de2f69392b7f25c@swarthmore-dash-calendar
DTSTAMP:20260308T112827Z
DTSTART:20260317T203000Z
DTEND:20260317T213000Z
SUMMARY:Sigma Xi Talk with Navid Saleh
DESCRIPTION:Organized by: ['Psychology']\\nCategory: Lecture/Panel Discussi
 on\\nWater\, Wisdom\, and Innovation: Blending Indigenous and Scientific P
 athways for Sustainable Design Technology alone cannot solve the water pol
 lution crisis in local and Indigenouscommunities. Its potential must be re
 conciled with the ethos of those it aims to serve and with the historical 
 mistrust bred by extractive practices. The global environmental engineerin
 g and science community has long worked to decontaminate water\, reduce sa
 linity\, and ensure a safe\,uninterrupted supply for millions. Yet\, those
  outside centralized water systems — those who have experienced systemic
  injustice or been deprived of access to safe water — may still be left 
 unserved by these efforts. At the same time\, many such communities posses
 s valuable holistic knowledge from which science can learn in addressing u
 nresolved challenges. It would be audacious for any discipline scarcely ha
 lf-a-millennium old to overlook knowledge forged overseventy millennia. Th
 is talk proposes a framework converging Indigenous and classical engineeri
 ng design pathways and aspires to serve as a catalyst for empathic design.
  Biography: Navid Saleh is the Jewel McAlister Smith Endowed Professorof M
 aseeh Department of Civil\, Architectural and EnvironmentalEngineering at 
 the University of Texas at Austin\, USA. He received hisPh.D. from Carnegi
 e Mellon University and was trained as a postdoctoralfellow at Yale Univer
 sity. Professor Saleh's research focuses on human-centered empathic design
  of nano-enabled water treatment technologies.Saleh research group works w
 ith Zapotec communities in Mexico\, Navajoand Alaska Natives in the US\, a
 nd the Chakma community in Bangladesh.Saleh’s research has produced 102 
 refereed publications and 7 bookchapters with more than 12\,000 citations 
 and an h-index of 45. Saleh’sresearch has been recently featured in PBS 
 NOVA’s documentary titled:Building Stuff: Change it! He serves as an Edi
 tor for the Journal of Hazardous Materials andTotal Environment Engineerin
 g. Dr. Saleh also served as the President of the Sustainable Nanotechnolog
 y Organization. He sits on the Editorial Boards of Environmental Science &
  Technology and Environmental Science: Nano.\\nDetails: https://swatcentra
 l.swarthmore.edu/?trumbaEmbed=view%3Devent%26eventid%3D1358837714
LOCATION:Kohlberg Hall Scheuer Room - Multi-Purpose Room
URL:https://swatcentral.swarthmore.edu/?trumbaEmbed=view%3Devent%26eventid%
 3D1358837714
CATEGORIES:Lecture/Panel Discussion
END:VEVENT
