SUMMARY:Genevieve Ching-wen Lee '96 Memorial Lecture
DESCRIPTION:Organized by: ['Asian American Studies']\\nCategory: Conference
 \\nSwarthmore CollegeAsian American Studies presents2026 Genevieve Ching-
 wen Lee '96 Memorial Lecture"How Asian American Studies Can Help You Fight
  Fascism: Joy as Resistance"Wednesday\, March 184:30 p.m. lecture with rec
 eption to followSproul 201\, Intercultural Center Dr. Jennifer HoProfesso
 r\, Ethnic StudiesDirector\, Center for Humanities & the ArtsUniversity of
  Colorado BoulderPast President\, Association for Asian American Studies (
 2020-2022)----The daughter of a refugee father from China and an immigrant
  mother from Jamaica\, whose parents themselves were immigrants from Hong 
 Kong\, Jennifer Ho is the director of the Center for Humanities & the A
 rts and Professor of Ethnic Studies at the University of Colorado Bould
 er\, where she specializes in Asian American literary and cultural studie
 s and Critical Race Theory. She is past president of the Association for A
 sian American Studies (2020-2022)\, the editor of four essay collections\,
  the author of three scholarly monographs and a number of essays and artic
 les\, both research oriented and public facing. In addition to her academi
 c work\, Ho is active in community engagement around issues of race and in
 tersectionality.Dr. Ho will discuss how in the 1960s\, activists of largel
 y Japanese\, Chinese\, Filipino/a/x\, and Korean descent came together out
  of radical organizing to create an umbrella term “Asian American” in 
 their fight for ethnic studies\, anti-war protest\, and solidarity with Bl
 ack civil rights. From that movement grew a field of study with roots in s
 ocial justice activism and political organizing. Over 60 years later the f
 ield of Asian American Studies has many lessons for anyone interested in f
 ighting against various forms of fascism\, such as the role of joy (especi
 ally through art\, food\, and music) in resisting authoritarianism. Dr. Je
 nnifer Ho will share observations rooted in her professional and personal 
 experiences with Asian American studies as a tool to fight fascism and to 
 promote joy as resistance in the authoritarian times we find ourselves in.
  \\nDetails: https://swatcentral.swarthmore.edu/?trumbaEmbed=view%3Devent
 %26eventid%3D1370669976
LOCATION:Hormel/Nguyen Intercultural Center at Sproul Hall Room 201 Dome Ro
 om
URL:https://swatcentral.swarthmore.edu/?trumbaEmbed=view%3Devent%26eventid%
 3D1370669976
CATEGORIES:Conference
END:VEVENT
