SUMMARY:P&A Colloquium: Sarah Burke-Spoalar\, West Virginia Univ
DESCRIPTION:Organized by: ['Physics and Astronomy']\\nCategory: Lecture/Pan
 el Discussion\\nSpring 2026  Physics and Astronomy Colloquium Sarah Burke
  SpolaorAssociate ProfessorWest Virginia UniversityDepartment of Physics a
 nd Astronomy Friday\, March 20\, 202612:45 pm Cunniff Lecture Hall (SCI 19
 9) MULTI-MESSENGER MONSTERS Sitting shrouded in darkness in the violent he
 arts of merging galaxies.... giant binary black holes are lurking. I will 
 tell you about work we are doing to uncover both electromagnetic and gravi
 tational waves from the biggest\, discrete binary systems in the Universe.
  When large galaxies merge\, these giant binaries can form. During their f
 inal inspiral\, they will produce intense gravitational radiation\, which 
 we have just begun to detect with gravitational-wave observatories like Pu
 lsar Timing Arrays. If there is gas in the system's environment\, they mig
 ht also be detectable in electromagnetic light. This talk will discuss our
  efforts to detect "multi-messenger" waves from binary supermassive black 
 holes using pulsar timing and electromagnetic light. This is worth knowing
  something about! -- Detailed studies of binary black holes\, their gravit
 y\, and their environments will be one of the major astronomical pursuits 
 between now and your eventual retirement. BIO: Dr. Burke-Spolaor is a prof
 essor in the Physics and Astronomy Department at WVU and a member of WVU's
  Center for Gravitational Waves and Cosmology (GWAC). She researches dynam
 ic phenomena: binary supermassive black holes\, cosmological sources of ra
 dio impulses\, pulsars\, and radio jets. The bulk of her work is on low-fr
 equency (nanoHertz) gravitational wave detection via pulsar timing\, searc
 hes for binary supermassive black holes to understand their evolution\, an
 d transient radio-emitting phenomena.  The colloquium will begin promptly
  at 12:45 p.m. in Science Center 199. A pizza lunch will be available at 1
 2:25 p.m. \\nDetails: https://swatcentral.swarthmore.edu/?trumbaEmbed=view
 %3Devent%26eventid%3D1358005006
LOCATION:Science Center Room 199-Cunniff Hall Tiered Classroom\, Science Ce
 nter Room 199-Cunniff Hall Lobby
URL:https://swatcentral.swarthmore.edu/?trumbaEmbed=view%3Devent%26eventid%
 3D1358005006
CATEGORIES:Lecture/Panel Discussion
END:VEVENT
